Project Prototype: "PostureSync"The Concept: An ergonomic health tracker that runs locally. It uses a webcam to monitor your seating posture in real time. Instead of just sending annoying notifications, it logs "posture scores" to a database and provides a sleek dashboard to track your ergonomic habits over days and weeks.This avoids the privacy concerns of cloud-based video streaming because the camera feed is processed entirely on the local device, and only the raw numeric data is sent to the database.The Tech StackThis architecture is divided into three clear layers, making it easy to split among a four-person team.The Computer Vision Engine (Python): Uses OpenCV and Google's MediaPipe library to detect body landmarks (shoulders, neck, ears). Math functions calculate the angles between these points to determine if the user is slouching.The Database & API (MySQL + FastAPI/Flask): A relational database is perfect here for time-series logging. The backend exposes a REST API that the Python script calls to log data, and that the frontend calls to retrieve data.The User Dashboard (React): A clean, component-based frontend that fetches the user's historical posture scores and renders them using charting libraries (like Chart.js or Recharts).System ArchitectureHere is how the data flows from the camera to the user's screen:Key insight: The bottleneck in this type of project is usually the database getting hammered with too many requests. The Python script should batch the posture scores (e.g., average them every 60 seconds) before sending a single POST request to the database, rather than sending a request every single frame.Database Schema (MySQL)To keep things efficient, you only need two core tables to get the MVP working:Table 1: Usersuser_id (Primary Key, UUID)username (VARCHAR)baseline_height (FLOAT) - Calibration data for their specific camera angle.Table 2: Posture_Logslog_id (Primary Key, Auto-Increment)user_id (Foreign Key)timestamp (DATETIME)posture_score (INT 1-100)alert_triggered (BOOLEAN) - Whether their posture was bad enough to warrant a desktop notification.
